metadata.name: De/Frag #305
metadata.description:
De/Frag is an homage to a classic algorithm in early computer art: Flood Fill. As a teenager in the late '80s, and without any literature, I spent weeks implementing a version for my very own drawing program for the Atari XL. It was the first non-trivial (to me) algorithm which made me want to learn more about data structures, the concept of recursion, divide-and-conquer...

Even though Flood Fill was available in most commercial drawing & office apps of the time, I gained a deep appreciation of the algorithm by building it from scratch myself. 30+ years later I know its aesthetic possibilities are still far from exhausted. This is an invitation for re-exploration by others too!

As with many design algorithms, my primary interest isn't even the final result, but observing the inner workings. I massively slowed down and time-sliced the process for this piece. I do recommend giving each of these unique versions some time to allow them to evolve their ever-changing patterns (Note: each piece never loops!).

metadata.name: Faux #12
metadata.description:
This project is borne out of my longstanding fascination with brushwork, and the intricate textures that can be created with a brush, some paint and a canvas. Brush strokes are simulated using many overlapping lines and given texture and depth using a custom shader. Another important aspect of this work, is the composite forms that are created by the brush strokes, which are my attempt to emulate the emphatic energy of many abstract painters that have come before me. Color palettes are named after common paint colors, based on the background color used for the palette.

Those who collect during the first tier of the Dutch Auction can claim a signed print. They will be printed on A3 Hahnemuhle Photo Rag, and shipped to the collector free of charge. More details on how to claim a print and specify the necessary shipping information will be provided via the artists twitter (@landlinesart1).

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #665
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Winesburg, Ohio #97
metadata.description: ‚ÄúWinesburg, Ohio‚Äù is an act of uncanny place-making. The collection borrows its name from a 1919 short-story cycle by Sherwood Anderson, which explores a peculiar cast of characters living within a fictionalized, midwestern town. Like Anderson‚Äôs text, the ‚ÄúWinesburg, Ohio‚Äù algorithm constructs a world through recurring portrayals of specific structures and landmarks. Its scenes are populated by a variety of familiar elements taken from my larger body of work, including water towers, houses, and churches. Meanwhile, a series of scripted gestures insert abstract compositional elements into the outputs, counteracting their pictorial legibility. The strange landscapes that result are composite ideograms, comprised of multiple spatial possibilities that co-exist in varying states of contradiction.

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #161
metadata.description:
‚ÄúOrdinary Places‚Äù is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher‚Äôs ‚ÄúWater Tower‚Äù photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha‚Äôs ‚Äú26 Gasoline Stations‚Äù photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather‚Äôs farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Concrete #315
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksj√∏ (1910‚Äì1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksj√∏ designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksj√∏‚Äôs aim was to ‚Äúsoften‚Äù modernist architecture. He invented ¬´Natural Concrete¬ª, a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions‚Äîusing code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksj√∏: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‚ÄòS‚Äô to save an image at current resolution or ‚ÄòP‚Äô to save a high-resolution file at 6000√ó6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau ¬∑ Made with p5.js & glsl ¬∑ Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: Reunion #152
metadata.description:
Reunion

---------------

Controls:
S: Export image at current scale
1-6: Change image scale (for higher quality downloads; default: 1)
F: Fit to screen (note that this can change the piece considerably; default: off)
G: Toggle grain (default: on)
O: Toggle border (default: off)
D: Toggle distortion (default: on)
A: Toggle chromatic abberation (default: on)
C: Toggle circles (default: on)
B: Toggle reversed B-side (default: off)

---------------

Outputs are generated using the minter's address as a seed. Each wallet is given a set of 25 seeds to look through. These are the only outputs that wallet can mint. Take your time and pick your favorite

---------------

Tyler Boswell (@teaboswell) 2023
